# Wine, Cheese & Gastronomy — Tasting Concepts & Pairing Principles

# ── Wine tasting fundamentals ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:terroir" "Concept of place: how soil, climate, topography, and local tradition shape a wine's character. From French 'terre' (earth). Fundamental to French AOC philosophy and Old World wine identity."
def "tasting:appellation" "Official geographic wine-growing area with legally regulated production rules, permitted varieties, and yields. Examples: AOC (France), DOC/DOCG (Italy), DO/DOCa (Spain), AVA (USA)."
def "tasting:vintage" "Year of grape harvest. Determines climate conditions during growing season and therefore ripeness, acidity, and aging potential. Critical for Champagne, Bordeaux, Burgundy, and Port declarations."
def "tasting:varietal" "Wine named after and made predominantly from a single grape variety (vs. blend or regional name). E.g. 'Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon.' Single-varietal disclosure required at 75-85% depending on country."
def "tasting:cepage" "French term for grape variety or varietal composition of a blend. Used in winemaker notes and French label law. 'Assemblage' refers to the act of blending cépages together."
def "tasting:millesime" "French term for vintage year as a mark of quality and character. A 'millésimé' Champagne is made from a single exceptional year vs. non-vintage (NV) which blends across years."

# ── Appearance descriptors ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:color_intensity" "Depth of wine's color from pale to deep. Influenced by grape variety, extraction time, and vintage ripeness. Pale: Pinot Gris, Riesling. Deep: Syrah, Malbec, Nebbiolo (despite pale hue)."
def "tasting:clarity" "Transparency and brilliance of wine in the glass. Ranges from brilliant (crystal clear) to hazy (some natural wines, unfiltered). Cloudiness can indicate fault or natural character."
def "tasting:viscosity" "Weight and thickness of wine in the glass; 'legs' or 'tears' running down the glass. Higher alcohol and sugar create more viscosity. Related to body but distinct from palate weight."

# ── Aroma categories ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:primary_aroma" "Aromas derived directly from the grape variety itself: fruit, floral, and herbal notes. Examples: blackcurrant in Cabernet, lychee in Gewurztraminer, grapefruit in Sauvignon Blanc."
def "tasting:secondary_aroma" "Aromas derived from fermentation processes (yeast, malolactic). Bread, cream, butter, cheese, yogurt. More prominent in wines with MLF, lees aging, or extended skin contact."
def "tasting:tertiary_aroma" "Aromas developed through aging in oak barrels or bottle (bouquet). Vanilla, toast, cedar, leather, earth, tobacco, truffle, dried fruit. Complex and only present in aged wines."

# ── Palate components ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:tannin" "Polyphenolic compounds from grape skins, seeds, stems, and oak barrels. Create drying, gripping sensation. High in: Nebbiolo, Tannat, Xinomavro, Cabernet Sauvignon. Binds with protein in food."
def "tasting:acidity" "Tartaric, malic, and citric acids in wine. Creates freshness, brightness, and food-friendliness. Key to aging potential. High acid: Riesling, Chablis, Champagne, Barbera, Sangiovese."
def "tasting:sweetness" "Residual sugar (RS) remaining after fermentation. Ranges from bone-dry (<1g/L) to lusciously sweet (>200g/L Trockenbeerenauslese). Perceived sweetness also affected by acidity and alcohol."
def "tasting:alcohol_level" "Ethanol content (% ABV). Adds body, warmth, and perceived sweetness. Low: 8-10% (Mosel Riesling Kabinett). Medium: 12-13%. High: 14-16% (Amarone, Zinfandel). Fortified: 17-22%."
def "tasting:body" "Overall weight and richness of wine on the palate. Light (Pinot Grigio, Muscadet), medium (Pinot Noir, Sangiovese), full (Shiraz, Chardonnay oaked, Grenache). Sum of tannin, alcohol, sugar, extract."
def "tasting:finish" "Length and persistence of flavor after swallowing. Short (<5 sec), medium (5-10 sec), long (10+ sec). Length correlates with quality; great wines have persistent, complex, evolving finish."
def "tasting:balance" "Harmony between wine's structural components: tannin, acidity, sweetness, and alcohol. No single element dominates. A key quality marker in classical wine assessment."
def "tasting:complexity" "Range and evolution of flavors and aromas in a wine. Multiple layers revealing different notes over time. Tertiary notes and structural evolution in glass indicate complexity. Key quality indicator."

# ── Flavor descriptor terms ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:fruit_forward" "Wine profile dominated by primary fresh fruit aromas and flavors. Common in New World wines and young vines. Blackberry, cherry, peach, melon dominate over earthy or mineral notes."
def "tasting:earthy" "Wine profile with soil, mushroom, forest floor, truffle, clay, or mineral notes. Classic in Old World wines: Burgundy Pinot Noir, Barolo, Rioja Reserva. Part of tertiary or terroir character."
def "tasting:mineral" "Wine descriptor for notes of flint, chalk, graphite, wet stone, saline, or oyster shell. Debated origin (soil, winemaking, chemistry). Hallmark of Chablis, Mosel Riesling, Assyrtiko."
def "tasting:floral" "Wine profile with flower aromas: violet (Nebbiolo, Syrah), rose (Gewurztraminer, Pinot Noir), orange blossom (Viognier, Muscat), elderflower (Sauvignon Blanc), jasmine (Riesling, Chenin)."
def "tasting:herbaceous" "Green, vegetal, or herbal notes: grass, green pepper (pyrazines in Cab Franc, Sauvignon Blanc), thyme, rosemary, bay leaf, eucalyptus. Can be varietal character or sign of under-ripeness."
def "tasting:spicy" "Pepper, clove, cinnamon, anise, or licorice notes. Black pepper in Syrah/Shiraz; white pepper in Grüner Veltliner; clove/cinnamon from oak aging; anise in Sangiovese and Tempranillo."
def "tasting:oaky" "Flavors imparted by barrel aging: vanilla, coconut, toast, caramel, cedar, sandalwood, smoke. New French oak strongest; American oak adds more vanilla/coconut. Undesirable when dominant."
def "tasting:buttery" "Rich, creamy butter or diacetyl note. Primarily from malolactic fermentation (malic → lactic acid conversion). Common in barrel-fermented oaked Chardonnay. Crème brûlée, popcorn adjacent."
def "tasting:smoky" "Smoky, ash, gunflint, or charcoal notes. Can come from terroir (volcanic soils: Santorini, Etna), oak char, or reduction. Pouilly-Fumé (Sauvignon Blanc over silex) is classic smoky terroir."

# ── Wine faults ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:brettanomyces" "Wine fault (or character) from Brettanomyces yeast. Barnyard, band-aid (adhesive), horse sweat, leather, medicinal phenols. In small amounts: complexity (Burgundy, old Rioja). In excess: flaw."
def "tasting:cork_taint" "Wine fault from TCA (2,4,6-trichloroanisole) contamination, usually from cork. Musty, moldy, damp cardboard smell. Suppresses fruit aromas. Affects ~2-5% of natural cork-sealed wines."
def "tasting:oxidation" "Exposure of wine to oxygen during production or storage. Sherry-like, nutty, flat, Madeira-esque notes in table wines when unintentional. Turns reds brown and whites dark amber. Fruit fades."
def "tasting:volatile_acidity" "Excess acetic acid (vinegar) in wine due to bacterial activity. A small amount adds complexity (Barolo). In excess: sharp, vinegary, pungent. Legal limits vary by country."
def "tasting:reduction" "Absence of oxygen during winemaking causing sulfur compounds (hydrogen sulfide, mercaptans). Struck match, rubber, cabbage, skunk notes. Often reversible by aeration; 'blown off' in glass."

# ── Oak and maturation techniques ─────────────────────────────────────────────

def "tasting:new_oak" "First-use oak barrel imparting maximum flavor: vanilla, coconut, toast, tannin. Used for aging Bordeaux, Rioja Gran Reserva, Napa Cabernet. Can overwhelm delicate varietals if excessive."
def "tasting:used_oak" "Second, third, or older-use oak barrels. Imparts less flavor; primarily for gentle oxygenation and micro-oxidation during aging. Used for Pinot Noir, lighter whites, and wines where oak subtlety needed."
def "tasting:malolactic_fermentation" "Secondary bacterial fermentation converting sharp malic acid to softer lactic acid. Reduces acidity, adds creaminess/butter. Standard for most reds; selective for whites (MLF Chardonnay vs. crisp Riesling)."
def "tasting:lees_aging" "Aging wine in contact with spent yeast cells (lees) after fermentation. Adds creaminess, bread dough, complexity, and mouthfeel. Sur lie aging standard in Muscadet, Champagne, some white Burgundy."
def "tasting:batonnage" "Stirring of wine lees during aging (French: bâtonnage). Integrates oak, adds richness and creaminess, prevents reduction. Practiced for barrel-aged Chardonnay and some red wines."

# ── Wine styles ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:style:still" "Non-sparkling, non-fortified wine. The vast majority of wine production. Dry, off-dry, sweet, and medium-sweet styles. Fermentation converts most or all sugar to alcohol."
def "wine:style:sparkling" "Wine with significant dissolved CO2 creating bubbles. Produced by secondary fermentation in bottle (traditional method) or tank (Charmat). Champagne, Cava, Prosecco, Sekt, Crémant, Pétillant Naturel."
def "wine:style:fortified" "Wine to which grape spirit (brandy) has been added, raising alcohol to 15-22% ABV. Stops fermentation if added early (Port, Vin Doux Naturel) or added after (Sherry, Madeira). Long shelf life."
def "wine:style:dessert" "Sweet wine with residual sugar from late harvest, noble rot, ice wine, or dried grape methods. Ranges from off-dry (Vouvray demi-sec) to intensely sweet (Sauternes, TBA, Vin Santo)."
def "wine:style:natural" "Wine made with minimal intervention: organic/biodynamic farming, native yeast fermentation, no additions (or minimal SO2), no fining or filtration. Hazy appearance common. Emerging global movement."
def "wine:style:biodynamic" "Wine made following Rudolf Steiner's biodynamic farming philosophy. Lunar calendar planting/harvesting, cow-horn compost preparations, holistic farm ecosystem approach. Demeter certification."
def "wine:style:orange_wine" "White wine made with extended skin contact (hours to months), giving amber color, tannins, and oxidative complexity. Ancient qvevri method revived in Friuli, Slovenia, and Georgia."
def "wine:style:pet_nat" "Pétillant Naturel — ancestral method sparkling wine bottled before fermentation completes. No dosage, no disgorging. Hazy, yeasty, wild character. Lower pressure than Champagne. Natural wine staple."
def "wine:style:methode_champenoise" "Traditional method (méthode champenoise/traditionnelle): secondary fermentation in bottle, aging on lees, riddling, disgorgement, dosage. Required for Champagne. Used in Cava, Crémant, English Sparkling."
def "wine:style:methode_ancestrale" "Ancestral method: wine bottled during primary fermentation. No addition of liqueur de tirage. Gentle bubbles, cloudy, often lower alcohol. Used in Blanquette de Limoux, Clairette de Die."
def "wine:style:charmat_method" "Tank (Charmat/Martinotti) method: secondary fermentation in pressurized tank, then bottled under pressure. Preserves fresh fruit aromatics. Used for Prosecco, Moscato d'Asti, most commercial sparkling."
def "wine:style:noble_rot" "Botrytis cinerea fungus infecting ripe grapes under specific humid/dry conditions. Concentrates sugars and adds honey, apricot, saffron notes. Essential for Sauternes, Tokaji Aszú, German BA/TBA."
def "wine:style:ice_wine" "Eiswein/Icewine: wine from grapes naturally frozen on vine (Germany, Austria, Canada). Extreme sugar/acid concentration when pressed frozen. Rare, expensive, intense. Canada is largest producer."
def "wine:style:late_harvest" "Wine from grapes left on vine past normal harvest, concentrating sugars. Degrees of ripeness: late harvest, select late harvest, botrytised. Style varies from off-dry to very sweet."
def "wine:style:dried_grape" "Wine from grapes dried post-harvest on mats (passito) or racks (appassimento). Concentrates sugar, flavor, and color. Amarone, Vin Santo, Recioto, Passito di Pantelleria are key examples."

# ── Pairing principles ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "pairing:mariage" "French term for ideal wine-food pairing: harmony between flavors, textures, and weight of wine and dish. A true mariage elevates both elements; neither overwhelms the other."
def "pairing:accord" "Harmonious wine-food pairing where wine and food share or complement flavor elements. Regional pairings (Burgundy Pinot with Burgundy beef), textural matches (creamy wine with creamy sauce)."
def "pairing:contraste" "Pairing by contrast: opposing flavor profiles that balance each other. Sweet wine with salty cheese, acidic wine with fatty food, tannic red with rich protein. Opposition creates harmony."
def "pairing:weight_matching" "Matching body and richness of wine to the richness and weight of the dish. Light wine with delicate fish; full-bodied red with hearty stew. The most fundamental pairing principle."
def "pairing:regional_pairing" "Traditional pairing of local wine with local cuisine. 'What grows together goes together.' Developed over centuries: Alsace Riesling with choucroute, Burgundy Pinot with boeuf bourguignon."
def "pairing:acid_cuts_fat" "Acidity in wine cuts through richness and fat, cleansing the palate. Champagne with fried food, Muscadet with oysters, Riesling with pork belly, Chianti with fatty Florentine steak."
def "pairing:tannin_binds_protein" "Red wine tannins bind with protein molecules in meat, softening the tannin's grip and amplifying the meat's umami. Barolo with bistecca, Cabernet with rib-eye, Syrah with lamb."
def "pairing:sweetness_with_saltiness" "Sweet wine complements salty foods by providing contrast. Sauternes with Roquefort, Port with Stilton, Jurancon with Roquefort, Tokaji Aszú with foie gras."
def "pairing:mirror_pairing" "Pairing where wine and food share similar flavor notes: earthy wine with earthy food (Burgundy + truffle), fruity wine with fruit-based dish (Riesling + apricot), smoky wine with smoked food."
def "pairing:bridge_ingredient" "Ingredient used in a dish that serves as a flavor bridge between food and wine. Mushrooms bridge earthiness, lemon bridges acidity, olive oil bridges Mediterranean wines."

# ── Cheese tasting and affinage ───────────────────────────────────────────────

def "cheese:tasting:affinage" "Art and science of maturing and aging cheese. An affineur (maturing specialist) controls humidity, temperature, turning, washing, and rind development. Transforms raw cheese into its final character."
def "cheese:tasting:rind" "Exterior crust or coating of cheese. Types: natural rind (wild molds), bloomy (white Penicillium camemberti), washed rind (brine/alcohol-washed orange rind), wax, cloth-bound, ash-covered."
def "cheese:tasting:paste" "Interior texture of cheese (distinct from rind). Descriptors: soft, semi-soft, semi-hard, hard, extra-hard (granular). Moisture content determines paste character and aging behavior."
def "cheese:tasting:eyes" "Holes in cheese formed by CO2 released by Propionibacterium bacteria during aging. Swiss cheeses (Emmental, Gruyère, Jarlsberg) are famous for large regular eyes. Small irregular holes also common."
def "cheese:tasting:mold" "Intentional mold cultures used in cheesemaking. Penicillium roqueforti: blue mold for Roquefort, Gorgonzola, Stilton. Penicillium camemberti: white bloomy rind for Brie, Camembert."
def "cheese:tasting:flora" "Bacteria and molds applied to or developing on cheese rind. Brevibacterium linens: orange-red washed rind for Munster, Époisses, Taleggio. Geotrichum candidum: wrinkled surface for some goat cheeses."
def "cheese:tasting:crystalline" "Texture descriptor: crunchy white crystals in aged hard cheese, composed of tyrosine amino acid crystals. Sign of proper long aging. Present in Parmigiano Reggiano 24+ months, aged Gouda, aged Cheddar."
def "cheese:tasting:creamy" "Texture descriptor: smooth, rich, coating mouthfeel in cheese. Characteristic of fresh cheese (burrata, ricotta), young soft-ripened (Brie), and high-fat formats (Brillat-Savarin, Vacherin)."
def "cheese:tasting:chalky" "Texture descriptor: dry, slightly gritty, powdery mouthfeel in young aged goat cheese. Characteristic of young Crottin de Chavignol, young Valençay. Transitions to creamy with further aging."
def "cheese:tasting:grainy" "Texture descriptor: small irregular particles on palate. Common in Pecorino Romano, young Parmigiano Reggiano, or hand-made fresh cheese. Indicates proteins not fully broken down."
def "cheese:tasting:springy" "Texture descriptor: elastic, rubbery, bouncy under pressure. Characteristic of fresh mozzarella, halloumi, young Havarti. High moisture and casein protein structure creates springy texture."
def "cheese:tasting:crumbly" "Texture descriptor: cheese that breaks into irregular pieces rather than cutting cleanly. Characteristic of Cheshire, Lancashire Crumbly, Wensleydale, dry-aged Pecorino, Roquefort."
def "cheese:tasting:supple" "Texture descriptor: pliable, flexible, smooth, not crumbly. Characteristic of Fontina, Reblochon, young Comté, Edam. Pleasant giving quality under finger pressure. Neither hard nor soft."
def "cheese:tasting:fudgy" "Texture descriptor: dense, moist, slightly sticky, intermediate between soft and semi-soft. Characteristic of some fresh goat cheeses, young Caerphilly, moist Wensleydale, certain washed rinds."

# ── Classic wine-cheese pairings ──────────────────────────────────────────────

ln wine:region:sauternes cheese:roquefort pairing:sweetness_with_saltiness
ln wine:region:champagne cheese:brie_de_meaux pairing:accord
ln wine:varietal:pinot_noir cheese:comte pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:region:porto_doc cheese:stilton pairing:sweetness_with_saltiness
ln wine:region:barolo cheese:parmigiano_reggiano pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:varietal:sauvignon_blanc cheese:crottin_de_chavignol pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:region:rioja cheese:manchego pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:varietal:riesling cheese:munster pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:region:madeira_do cheese:comte pairing:accord
ln wine:varietal:assyrtiko cheese:feta pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:region:bordeaux cheese:cantal pairing:accord
ln wine:region:alsace cheese:munster pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:varietal:nebbiolo cheese:gorgonzola pairing:contraste
ln wine:region:jerez cheese:manchego pairing:regional_pairing
ln wine:region:tokaj_hungary cheese:epoisses pairing:accord

